    <prj:ScienceGoal>
        <prj:name>The shortest time-scale of polarization variability of a quasar 1334-127</prj:name>
        <prj:note>Even if several studies aimed at the analysis of AGN polarization at various timescales, the behaviour of AGN polarization is unknown at the shortest timescales available, in the range from seconds to minutes. This is very important since AGN polarization variability has not been found on all timescales ever probed, from tens of seconds to tens of years. This implies that a genuine minimum timescale of AGN polarization activity has not been
found yet. This leads to an essential question, Is there a shortest time-scale of AGN polarization activity? One minimum scale may be set by the light travel time across the Schwarzschild radius of the central black hole, i.e. few minutes typically. Other short timescales can be established by the orbit period at the innermost stable orbit around the black hole as well as the size of shocked regions or cells in AGN jets. Another question immediately followed by the first one is What is the origin of the shortest time-scale variability of polarized emission?. Depending on the time-scales and behavious of the variability, we may be able to constrain its origin among those described above.</prj:note>
