        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>For addressing the questions, we propose to conduct polarization observations of a highly polarized blazar J1337-1257 (z = 0.539) with ALMA at the band 3. Its radio spectrum is quite flat in the radio-to-millimeter range (0.3–100 GHz).  In VLBI observations at 5 GHz, J1337-1257 showed the polarization variability at hour-scales. Recently, KVN single dish polarization observations of J1337-1257 showed polarized flux of 258 mJy (p = 3.35%, pa= 58 deg) and 230 mJy (p = 3.24%, pa = 45deg) at 22 and 43 GHz bands, respectively. The estimated Faraday rotation measure (RM) is RM =1.7 × 10^3 rad m−2. The source also showed highly polarized flux of 339 mJy (p = 7.13%) at 86 GHz band. The source is also in the list of ALMA bandpass calibrator sources (Table A.4 of ALMA Cycle 2 Technical Handbook, v1.1) with slightly different name and coordinates (J1337-129). Its representative flux at the ALMA Band 3 is 5.93 Jy, which is higher by 25% than that reported by Agudo et al. 2010. In order to obtain polarization measurement as at shortest time-scale as possible, we plan to produce snapshot images at integration times ranging from seconds to minutes. The ALMA sensitivity calculator gives an rms sensitivity of 0.78 mJy for a dual polarization image of J1337-1257 with integration time of 1 sec, observing frequency of 95 GHz, bandwidth per polarization of 7.5 GHz, and 34 antenna in 12-m Array. With the estimated sensitivity of 0.78 mJy at the 1 second-integration, we may be able to detect the variation of polarized emission with an amplitude of Sp = 2.34 mJy (\delta p &gt; 0.05%) for the target source. We note that the value \delta p should be different from the polarization detection limit of 0.3% We request to reach the sensitivity of the observation to 0.78 mJy during 3 hours, to minimize the overheads, and to maximize the on-source integration time. Since the minimum dump rate of the ALMA correlator is 16 msec, we may push the sampling time to 16 ms and hence the shortest time-scale of variation to 32 ms. In this case we will have the sensitivity of 6.1 mJy for a snapshot image. In order to maintain the accurate calibration for whole observation, we, however, request to reach the sensitivity of the observation to 0.78 mJy during 3 hours, to minimize the overheads, and to maximize the on-source integration time.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
