    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We propose polarization observations of a blazar J1337-1257 at 100 GHz band with ALMA. Our main goals are a) to find a genuine minimum time-scale of Active Galactic Nuclei (AGN) polarization variability that has not been found yet, and b) to find the origin of the shortest time-scale variability in the AGN. We aim at rapid polarization observation with sampling times ranging from a second to minutes during three hours. This allows us to probe the shortest time-scale of variability of polarized emission at millimeter wavelength observed in AGN. We intend to seek for the fast variability of fractional linear polarization, linear polarization angle, and in-band Faraday rotation measure (RM). Our analysis requires long (3 hours), finely sampled (approx. 1 sec), well calibrated measurements of polarized emission.</prp:abstract>
